                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d732">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/10–3148: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="30" xml:id="d732fn30">Repeated as telegram No. 192,
                        November 3, to the Consul General at Mukden.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-11-01T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 1, 1948—4 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1519. Re Mukden’s 457 [<hi rend="italic">456</hi>] Oct 31,<note n="31"
                        xml:id="d732fn31">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_530">p. 530</ref>. Mukden was
                        occupied by Chinese Communist forces on November 1.</note> rptd Nanking as
                    606. Emb authorized in its discretion approach Chinese authorities and ask
                    whether CAF plans bomb Mukden. If reply negative inform Chinese you will so
                    inform your Govt. If reply affirmative, Emb should point out sites Mukden where
                    Americans located and express hope that any possible post-surrender bombing of
                    Mukden be carefully limited to targets of military significance.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
